<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-431-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 431 234.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  May 1990 v7 n3 p31(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>User-interface development tools.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lee, Ed; Hall, Frank; Bowers, Andrea; Yang, Sherry; Bass, Len;Lemke, Andreas; Shan, Yen-Ping.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Research institutions and companies are working on developingbetter user-interface software architectures and productivitytools.andP;  The approaches include tools kits, which are libraries ofcomponents; user-interface management systems, a softwarearchitecture which has clearly separated user interface andunderlying functionality; and interactive design tools, which letthe user use tool kits or user-interface management systems moreproductivity.andP;  HP and Visual Edge Software are developing UIMX, aninteractive design tool that works as a rapid-development tool.andO;JYACC's Jam is used to prototype, design, and build textualapplications.andP;  Speedcode from Oregon State University works on theMacintosh and permits direct manipulation of user-interfaceobjects so no explicit coding is needed.andP;  Software EngineeringInstitute's Serpent UIMS permits the user to separate anapplication from the user interface details and manages aninterface's dynamic behavior.andP;  Framer from the University ofColorado at Boulder uses knowledge-based technology to shorten thedesign/implementation/testing cycle.andP;  Mode from the University ofNorth Carolina at Chapel Hill uses direct manipulation to createuser interfaces.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   JYACC Inc. (products).andO;Product:   JAM (Computer program) (usage).andO;Topic:     User InterfaceApplications ProgrammingSoftware ArchitectureProgram Development Tools.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>